title: For Sale:  Concealed Handgun License Class
postcontent: **Quarterly CHL class offered October 15th, 2016, register now!** The Newberg Rifle and Pistol Club is a premier training facility for concealed handgun certification in the Portland area. Our instructors have extensive NRA certifications and  combine the disciplines of law enforcement, military, and civilian shooting to provide the student with a unique learning experience. Additionally we offer a live fire segment after the class, at no additional charge. Coached live fire is something very few training facilities offer as part of certification training. The Utah, Arizona and Florida permits are useful for travelers as they are honored in many more states then the Oregon CHL. With the training you will also receive fingerprinting on the appropriate cards and passport style photos to complete your applications. The cost schedule for endorsements is: Oregon $50.00 Oregon plus one other state $100 Oregon plus two other states $130 All four states $160 One state without Oregon $80 Two states without Oregon $115 Three states without Oregon $150 Classroom instruction is expected to last three to four hours depending on endorsements. Live fire is conducted at our indoor range under the supervision of the Chief Range Officer. Individual coaches will assist each shooter participating in the exercise. It is suggested the participants bring their own handgun and fifty rounds of factory new ammunition. Each personal firearm will be inspected to ensure it is fully functional and in safe condition for use in the live fire exercise. The concealed handgun course is presented Quarterly on the third (3rd) Saturday of: January, April, July and October. The course is conducted at NRPC’s Indoor Range located at 15955 NE Quarry Rd, Newberg, OR 97132 For questions about the course and content, contact NRPC President John Harris at REDACTED or respond to this post. Visit our website, nrpc.net

title: For Sale:  Ruger Vaquero Birdshead Case Hardened Frame
postcontent: Up for sale is an ultra rare Ruger single action...more on the rare part in a minute. This is a large frame (original Vaquero), not the current "New Vaquero" model. The large frame originals are capable of "Ruger only" loads. It's the blued model with Ruger's faux case hardened frame. The revolver exhibits a slight turn line on the cylinder from handling but has not been fired outside of the Ruger factory. The model number is 00511 and the catalog number is BNVBH-453. Now the backstory on the rare part....Ruger transitioned from the original Vaquero to the new Vaquero late 2004 early 2005 timeframe and stopped making the originals. Thus gun was made in April of 2010 (based on the spent shell casing that came with it from the factory), 5 years after the end of production and 5 years after Ruger stopped the faux case hardening on their blued single actions. Furthermore, the notorious Ruger warning label on the barrel was much smaller and on the underside of the barrel. Prior examples were larger and on the side of the barrel. After acquiring, I called Ruger to verify the manufacter date. Between that and the model/catalog number (which were unique to this particular gun), I was able to find out through a few searches this was one of Ruger's parts clean up releases that were only sold through Davidson's, and that there were likely less than 200 or so made. The late production alone makes it a Ruger collector's object of desire, but the barrel warning label variation puts it over the top. If interested, feel free to reply with your number. I'd be happy to text additional pictures, including the factory label showing model/catalog as well as the dated spent casing. Price is $700

title: For Sale:  Finnish Mosin Nagant M24 91/24
postcontent: This is a Finnish Mosin Nagant M24. It is a SIG Stepped Barrel, with the "Christmas Tree" mark from the barrel being shortened at the throat. This is also visible with the Swiss Barrel company's emblem being partially obscured where the receiver meets the barrel. This rifle was originally a 1917 Russian M91, with the date confirmed under the tang and the Imperial Eagle still visible on the hex receiver. Research into the Finnish serial numbers indicates this rifle was assigned to the Pirkka Hame district. Barrel bands are early Russian, with captured screws. A Russian cartouche on the buttstock is still faintly visible. The sling hangers are Finnish. None of the numbers match, typical with most Finnish captured rifles. I have function-checked and dry-fired the rifle without issue. The bore is clean and in very good shape. This was going to go on gunbroker but my computer and JAVA don't get along. The high asking price is due to the fact a very similar rifle sold for over $1800 on that website last year.  If you have a serious interest in the rifle, we'll talk about the price and I'll send over several more photos. I must sell this rifle as is, due to the high risk it may come back missing parts or altered. I will give preference to C&R FFL holders (I am one) and will ship with extreme caution taken via insurance and packaging.
